# Sequential Logic and Memory

Unlike the combinational chips we built in projects 1 and 2, memory chips have **state** — they remember values over time. This requires a clock and sequential logic.

## The Clock and Time

In digital circuits, a clock signal alternates between 0 and 1 at a constant frequency. All state changes happen on the clock's rising edge (transition from 0 to 1). This synchronizes the entire system.

## Data Flip-Flop (DFF)

The DFF is the primitive sequential gate. Its output follows the input, but delayed by one clock cycle:

```
out(t) = in(t-1)
```

## Bit Register

A Bit chip stores a single binary value. It can be written to (when load=1) or read back (when load=0).

```hdl
CHIP Bit {
    IN in, load;
    OUT out;
    PARTS:
    Mux(a=dffOut, b=in, sel=load, out=muxOut);
    DFF(in=muxOut, out=dffOut);
    // out = dffOut
}
```

## Register

A 16-bit Register stores a whole word — 16 Bit chips in parallel:

```hdl
CHIP Register {
    IN in[16], load;
    OUT out[16];
    PARTS:
    Bit(in=in[0], load=load, out=out[0]);
    Bit(in=in[1], load=load, out=out[1]);
    // ... 14 more bits ...
}
```

## RAM

RAM chips extend registers into arrays: RAM8 (8 registers), RAM64, RAM512, RAM4K, RAM16K. Each uses a **RAM counter** for address decoding.

## Program Counter (PC)

The PC holds the address of the next instruction. It supports three operations: reset (load address 0), next (increment), and jump (load a new address).

```hdl
CHIP PC {
    IN in[16], load, inc, reset;
    OUT out[16];
    // Increments, loads, or resets on each clock tick
}
```

